The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Barclays pledges $70 m more

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 Roberts: Glad tidings

 Mumbai, March 21: Financial services provider Barclays plc will infuse fresh funds into India to tap new segments in commercial and corporate banking and expand its investment banking business. 

 The bank will invest $70 million in the next two years to raise its presence in corporate banking, a month after pumping in $150 million into its Indian operations.

 In India for more than a quarter of a century, Barclays is involved in investment banking and risk management. It offers both onshore and offshore debt financing facilities and is a major player in convertible bonds market, having structured deals worth $1.287 billion since January last year.

 In addition to multinationals, Barclays is keen to rope in clients from the small and medium enterprises (SMEs) sector in the areas of supply chain financing, trade finance, risk management and corporate liquidity management. 

 Moreover, with India Inc eyeing overseas companies, Barclays wants to finance these acquisitions.

 According to David Roberts, board member of Barclays plc and chief executive of the banks international retail and commercial banking operations, the bank is awaiting the Reserve Bank of Indias approval to set up branches outside Mumbai, as part of an organic expansion strategy. The bank has a branch in Mumbai.

 Roberts said Barclays is scouting for quality talent to lead its India charge. The corporate banking business will employ around 150 people in the medium term with 40 being recruited in the first year. This is in addition to the over 40 employees engaged in investment banking operations. 




